binding.p: Late medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 4 double spinebands and endbands. 2 hook-clasp fastenings, 2 different styles of catch plates on . Spine: stamped in gold: A 35; in black ink: 89; in brown ink on a sticker: A. 35 ; remains of a torn-off sticker.
binding.decoNote: Blind tooling with series of frames and diagonal lines creating lozenges, in which are stamped roses and fleur-de lys of two sizes.
binding.condition: Leather torn, especially on the spine where the endbands are visible. Several small holes in the upper part of . Clasps detached and preserved separately.

history.origin:
Denmark , probably Viborg diocese, after 1489. Regarding the origin former librarian Anna Wolodarski has observed that the liturgical contents agree to some extant with the liturgical traditions of the Danish dioceses of Slesvig, Odense and Århus, but the highest degree of solemnity of St Kjeld (Kettil) and the strong Augustinian features point to the diocese of Viborg, Jutland (for which no breviary has been preserved). The Birgittine and Franciscan influences are obvious. The great number of saints not found in the liturgical traditions of the Danish dioceses might imply a martyrology as a model for the manuscript. The rubrics In cicilia natalis sanctorum lxxxiiii (), In Britania deposicio Felicis episcopi () and the obit: Hic obiit Vademarus rex Danorum (, relating to Valdemar I ‘the Great’) could confirm this suggestion, see Helander (1989)
and Andersen (1990)
. The feminine grammatical forms in both the Latin prayers for Sophia (, famula) and in one of the vernacular prayers (, syndherskæ) point to a female owner. Regarding the dating: the feast of Catherine of Sweden implies dating after 1489, see Andersen (1990)
; according to Chesnutt (2003) a date shortly after 1500 is plausible.
history.provenance:
The manuscript has been in Sweden since at least the 17th century. It may have been taken as war booty. The signum no. 14 (), possibly written by Johan Hadorph jr., probably refers to the arrangement of the library of the College of Antiquities from about 1689, cf. Ilsøe (1968)
. The manuscript belonged to the Antiquities Archive and is listed in its inventories and catalogues.
The older signum 89 is mentioned in the inventory from the 1720s (U 90:2, f. 8).
Current signum, A 35, first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720s (U 91:2:2).
Also mentioned in the following catalogues and inventories: U 90:1, f. 12v no. 144; (U 91:1) G 89, later changed to 35; U 91:5 no. 54.
history.acquisition: From the Antiquities Archive to the National Library in .

msItem.title: Proper of saints
msItem.rubric: Hic incipit de Sanctis primo de sancto stephano antiphona
msItem.incipit: Intuens in celum beatus stephanus uidit gloriam dei
msItem.explicit: sic eius munera capiamus sempiterna gaudentes Per eundem qui theodosie virginis eodem die.

note.p: The Proper of saints begins with St Stephen (26 Dec.) and ends with St Thomas (21 Dec.) and with the rubric for St Theodosia (18 July).
A majority of the pages only contain the rubric for a each feast.
Notable feasts:
: St Henry (19 Jan., text not inserted);
: St Sigfrid (15 Feb.);
: St Lucius (4 Mar.);
: St Katarina of Sweden (24 Mar.);
: St Halward (15 May, text not inserted);
: Erik (18 May);

: St Vilhelm, 16 June;

: St Birgitta (23 July, text after the office Rosa rorans);
: St Olaf (29 July);
: translation of St Lucius (25 Aug.);

: St Birigtta (7 Oct., text after the office Birgitte matris inclite);

p.note: The first and centre bifolium of every quire is parchment, everything else paper.

watermark.term: Letter P, above single line rod with flower on top.
watermark.note: Similar to watermarks in Piccard IV:2, chapters VII-VIII. There may be two or more versions of P-marks, but they are difficult to analyse because of the text. The most visible watermark is on , additional ones on e.g. and .
